In adults, systolic blood pressure rises from early adulthood onward, up to at least age 70. Las ecuaciones para estimar la tasa de filtración glomerular (GFR) son normalmente utilizadas para valorar la función renal. La mayoría de las ecuaciones tradicionales tienen una precisión limitada. Recientemente se ha desarrollado y publicado una nueva ecuación para el cálculo de la GFR. Se trata de la ecuación CKD-EPI que se ha demostrado ser más más exacta que otras ecuaciones más tradicionales. Las variables incluidas en la ecuación CKD-EPI para estimar la GFR son el valor de la creatinina sérica (expresada bien en umol/L o en mg/dL), el sexo, la raza y la edad. En recientes publicaciones de estudios realizados, ha quedado patente que la ecuación CKD-EPI es más exacta que la ecuación del estudio MDRD a lo largo de una gran variedad de poblaciones y condiciones clínicas. Esta mayor exactitud de la ecuación CKD-EPI puede beneficiar la estimación de la función renal en la práctica clínica diaria. 

Esta aplicación le permitirá realizar cálculos de la GFR a través de la ecuación CKD-EPI de una forma sencilla, rápida e intuitiva. Una vez realizados los cálculos, usted podrá enviarse un breve informe a una cuenta de correo electrónico. Además podrá consultar la publicación científica donde se explica el racional para el desarrollo de la fórmula CKD-EPI.

The annual cost of sepsis treatment to the US healthcare system is $23.7 billion dollars, making sepsis the most expensive condition treated in US hospitals. 

The key to surviving sepsis is rapid recognition and treatment with antibiotics, fluids and other drugs that stabilize blood pressure. Current guidelines recommend administering IV antibiotics within 1 hour of diagnosis, and giving IV fluids and performing other treatment steps within 3 and 6 hours depending on symptom severity. However, in busy hospital environments, delays can easily occur leading to avoidable complications and deaths.

Sepsis Timer is a timed checklist and simple clinical decision support tool designed to help busy hospital clinicians perform key treatment steps within prescribed time intervals. Simply start a timer when a patient is diagnosed with sepsis and the app will list the necessary treatment steps and alert you when these steps are due. To turn off the alerts, simply check off the required steps. 

The treatment steps and timelines used in Sepsis Timer are based on Surviving Sepsis Campaign (SSC) guidelines that are also recommended by the Institute of Healthcare Improvement (IHI) and the US Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS).

Sepsis Timer features include:
- Compliance with SSC sepsis bundles, and IHI and CMS SEP-1 Core Measure sepsis treatment guidelines
- Simple and intuitive user interface
- Configurable alert options include periodic and snooze alerts with customizable sounds
- Response time tracking records time to completion of treatment steps and bundles
- Simple statistical report shows average response times for completed timers over time
- Thorough user manual and explanations for all treatment steps and app functions
- Basic background information on sepsis diagnosis and treatment; for more in-depth information please use our Sepsis Clinical Guide app

This app is intended for physicians, nurses and other healthcare professionals managing the care of critically ill patients in a hospital environment.

The Commonwealth Pharmacists Association (CPA) is a registered charity, working across the Commonwealth and other countries, to support pharmacists in strengthening healthcare systems through the safe and effective use of medicines; improving access to and quality of medicines and vaccines, the prevention of diseases and promotion of healthier lifestyles.

About the Prescribing Companion App

Welcome to the Prescribing Companion App! Led by the CPA the App hosts for the first time, a core repository of prescribing resources in both human and animal health, to drive Antimicrobial Stewardship (AMS). By increasing awareness of prescribing guidelines and improving access to good practice resources at the point of care, we aim to foster shared learning between countries across human and animal health and align to the global One Health approach.

Intended for use by human and animal healthcare professionals, the App is a reference resource for guidance on antimicrobial prescribing and broader AMS activities. It does not replace the advice of a healthcare professional. Each individual country (not the CPA) holds responsibility for reviewing and keeping the resources up-to-date, for their country section.

While the initial scope of the App is AMS, it can be further customized by individual country needs; such as guidelines and resources for different therapeutic areas. The App is a continuous work in progress, with ring-fenced funding until 2027. Each country is able to regularly update and add resources that meet their requirements, ensuring that it truly reflects local needs and usage.

ToolKits

Under each country interface are a number of toolkits which contain the following:

Infections and infectious disease Prescribing

This toolkit includes national standard antimicrobial treatment guidelines from countries in the initial project cohort. Countries interested in using the App can be supported to upload their guidelines.

Other common clinical conditions

A customizable section where countries can add standard treatment guidelines in other clinical areas such as hypertension, maternity etc

International AMS and Infection Prevention and Control (IPC)

A number of international core modules and good practice guidelines in human health are available for all 22 countries. These are embedded as links to third party websites including WHO and CDC. Some CPA programme tools and training resources are also found in this section.

COVID-19 Toolkit

International resources for COVID-19 management as well as links to country specific guidance hosted on Ministry of Health websites or relevant national authority.

Interventional Recording

Currently contains an audit form, developed by the SPARC programme, to identify the range of interventions made by health professionals as a result of using the App. Similar forms can be added to collect a vast range of data.

Animal Health

Due to a current global scarcity of animal health guidance at international and national levels, we have identified some core resources to support animal health practitioners. Resources include The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) - Action plan on Antimicrobial resistance (2021-2025) and an AMR hub to support veterinarians. Where available, national standard antimicrobial treatment guidelines for animals have been included.

This section is a work in progress and we welcome further resources.

Accessibility Statement

The App is freely available and has been designed to function offline once toolkits are downloaded.

Development & Funding

The App is part of the CPA’s SPARC programme, funded by the Fleming Fund, which delivered a suite of projects to support AMS in human and animal health, in up to 22 countries across Asia and Africa. It is developed using the Quris system from Tactuum.
